<DOC><DOCNO> AP890803-0217 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-89 2127EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-03 0278</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Panama,0287</SECOND><HEAD>Student Demonstrator Killed, Six Wounded by Defense Forces</HEAD><DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Troops opened fire on an oppositiondemonstration at the University of Panama Thursday, killing onestudent and wounding at least six people, university and hospitalsources said.   The Defense Forces would not comment on the incident.   Witnesses said the confrontation took place during a rally byabout 100 students who want the results of a May 7 electionrecognized. The students were protesting a proposal by theOrganization of American States for a new national election.   International observers had said the opposition candidateGuillermo Endara was winning the May 7 election by a 3-1 marginwhen the government, controlled by Defense Forces chief AntonioManuel Noriega, stopped vote tallying and voided the election.   Witnesses said demonstrators threw rocks at riot troops and thetroops opened fire.   Hospital and university sources said a 24-year-old man shot atvery close range with birdshot died at nearby Bella Vista Clinic.They said at least six other demonstrators were wounded.   The witnesses and the officials spoke on condition of anonymity.   A negotiating team from the OAS is in Panama trying to helpresolve the election. The opposition wants recognition of itselectoral victory and Gen. Noriega's departure from power.   Noriega was indicted in Florida in February 1988 on drugtrafficking and money laundering charges, which he denied.President Eric Delvalle tried to fire Noriega as Defense Forceschief following the U.S. charges, but Noriega maneuvered to havethe National Assembly dismiss Delvalle, who the United States stillrecognizes as president.   The United States imposed economic sanctions on Panama, amongother measures aiming to force Noriega from power.</TEXT></DOC>